{"slideshow_credits": null, "snippet": "Doing business by phone or laptop while traveling can attract the prying eyes or ears of fellow passengers and unwittingly reveal company secrets.", "abstract": null, "section_name": "Technology; Business", "print_page": "1", "document_type": "article", "byline": {"person": [{"firstname": "David", "role": "reported", "lastname": "WALLIS", "rank": 1, "organization": ""}], "original": "By DAVID WALLIS"}, "web_url": "http://www.nytimes.com/2012/05/03/business/taking-business-calls-on-the-train-watch-what-you-say.html", "lead_paragraph": "PETER COCHRANE, a technology consultant, entrepreneur and blogger, usually unwinds on the train between his home in Ipswich, England, and London with coffee, cookies and a newspaper. But during a memorable trip in March 2006, neighboring passengers disturbed his relaxation rituals by behaving in a very un-British manner: They were loud.", "headline": {"main": "Loose Lips Can Sink Trips"}, "_id": "4fd2bba98eb7c8105d8b1a51", "word_count": 1514, "multimedia": [{"height": 75, "url": "images/2012/05/03/business/SNOOP/SNOOP-thumbStandard.jpg", "legacy": {"thumbnail": "images/2012/05/03/business/SNOOP/SNOOP-thumbStandard.jpg", "hasthumbnail": "Y", "thumbnailwidth": 75, "thumbnailheight": 75}, "subtype": "thumbnail", "width": 75, "type": "image"}, {"height": 330, "url": "images/2012/05/03/business/SNOOP/SNOOP-articleLarge.jpg", "legacy": {"xlarge": "images/2012/05/03/business/SNOOP/SNOOP-articleLarge.jpg", "xlargewidth": 600, "xlargeheight": 330, "hasxlarge": "Y"}, "subtype": "xlarge", "width": 600, "type": "image"}], "pub_date": "2012-05-02T00:00:00Z", "source": "The New York Times", "news_desk": "Business Day", "keywords": [{"name": "subject", "value": "WIRELESS COMMUNICATIONS"}, {"name": "subject", "value": "BUSINESS TRAVEL"}, {"name": "subject", "value": "COMPUTERS AND THE INTERNET"}], "blog": [], "subsection_name": null, "type_of_material": "News"}